<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">In the modern world of construction, the =
need for air conditioning systems that are both highly efficient and compat=
ible with diverse architectural structures and smart energy consumption is =
felt more than ever.&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://greenac.co/en/posts/6728e54794=
04212c38fe6913" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener">VRF </a>(Variable Refrig=
erant Flow) systems have become one of the top choices in large residential=
, commercial, office and hotel projects due to their high design flexibilit=
y, low energy consumption and the ability to independently control each spa=
ce. But choosing the right system requires careful consideration of technic=
al factors, project needs, and design principles. In this article, we will =
help you become familiar with the guiding principles for selecting and desi=
gning a VRF system and make an informed, economic, and technical decision.<=
/p>
<h1 style=3D"text-align: justify;" id=3D"toc-heading-1-key-parameters-in-se=
lecting-a-vrf-system"><br><span style=3D"font-size: 14pt;"><strong>Key Para=
meters in Selecting a VRF System</strong></span></h1>
<h3 style=3D"text-align: justify;" id=3D"toc-heading-2-building-cooling-and=
-heating-load"><br><span style=3D"color: rgb(224, 62, 45);"><strong>Buildin=
g Cooling and Heating Load</strong></span></h3>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">The first and most important step is to a=
ccurately calculate the building's heating and cooling load using reputable=
 software such as HAP or Carrier. This information is the basis for designi=
ng a VRF system and helps in selecting the number of units and the capacity=
 of the device.</p>
<h3 style=3D"text-align: justify;" id=3D"toc-heading-3-type-of-use-and-spac=
e-plan"><span style=3D"color: rgb(224, 62, 45);"><strong>Type of use and sp=
ace plan</strong></span></h3>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">Commercial buildings, hotels, medical cen=
ters or offices, require different designs due to differences in space usag=
e patterns. For example, in hotels, the need for independent heating and co=
oling in rooms is vital, and in offices, central control and BMS are more i=
mportant.</p>
<h3 style=3D"text-align: justify;" id=3D"toc-heading-4-number-and-type-of-i=
ndoor-units"><span style=3D"color: rgb(224, 62, 45);"><strong>Number and ty=
pe of indoor units</strong></span></h3>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">Depending on the type of architecture, ce=
iling height, interior decoration and type of space (room, hall, corridor),=
 various types of indoor units (wall-mounted, built-in ceiling, ducted, fou=
r-way cassette, etc.) can be used. The capacity of each unit should be sele=
cted based on the load of that space.</p>
<h3 style=3D"text-align: justify;" id=3D"toc-heading-5-outdoor-unit-install=
ation-location"><span style=3D"color: rgb(224, 62, 45);"><strong>Outdoor Un=
it Installation Location</strong></span></h3>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">The space limitations for installing the =
outdoor unit should be determined from the beginning. The installation loca=
tion should have adequate ventilation, a reasonable distance from the indoo=
r units, and access for periodic servicing.</p>
<h3 style=3D"text-align: justify;" id=3D"toc-heading-6-refrigerant-piping-r=
oute"><span style=3D"color: rgb(224, 62, 45);"><strong>Refrigerant piping r=
oute</strong></span></h3>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">The piping between the units should be de=
signed with minimal bends, appropriate slope, and within the allowed length=
 range. Paying attention to pressure drop, oiling, and preventing oil backf=
low are important technical points in route design.</p>
<h3 style=3D"text-align: justify;" id=3D"toc-heading-7-power-consumption-an=
d-building-power-capacity"><span style=3D"color: rgb(224, 62, 45);"><strong=
>Power consumption and building power capacity</strong></span></h3>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">The total system power consumption, compr=
essor power, power type (single-phase or three-phase), and coordination wit=
h the electrical panel and diesel generator (if any) should be checked.</p>
<h3 style=3D"text-align: justify;" id=3D"toc-heading-8-controllers-and-smar=
t-management"><span style=3D"color: rgb(224, 62, 45);"><strong>Controllers =
and Smart Management</strong></span></h3>
<p style=3D"text-align: justify;">The VRF system should be able to connect =
to a central control panel, timer, occupancy sensor, or building management=
 system (BMS). These increase efficiency and ease of use.</p>
